1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper deals with an online algorithm for an energy harvesting transmitter, where the transmission time is considered as the system performance. This involves the optimization of the transmit power based on the current battery energy level and the data queue length directly monitored by the transmitter itself. This falls under the purview of information theory. 
2. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper formulates the design as a robust-optimal control problem which aims to optimize the worst-case performance. This involves the use of control theory to optimize the performance of the system. 
3. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper deals with an energy harvesting transmitter, which is a key component in wireless networks. The proposed design can be used to optimize the performance of such networks. 
4. cs.MA (Multiagent Systems): The paper deals with an online algorithm for an energy harvesting transmitter, which can be seen as an agent in a multi-agent system. The proposed design can be used to optimize the performance of such systems. 
5. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing): The proposed design involves the use of an event-trigger approach, which can be seen as a form of distributed computing.
